{
  "texts": [
    "In other words, agents don't seek only to minimize prediction error in the present but are sensitive to rates of change in prediction error minimisation over time, relative to their prior expectations about that rate, i.e., whether they are reducing error better than, or slower than expected (Joffily & Coricelli, 2013; Van de Cruys, 2017; Kiverstein et al., 2019; Hesp et al., 2021).",
    "The sense of rising frustration we feel while sitting in an unexpected traffic jam reflects us minimizing error (relative to the action-guiding prediction of arriving soon at our destination) more slowly than expected (e.g., Eldar et al., 2016.",
    "See also: Barrett, 2017; Barrett & Simmons, 2016; Barrett et al., 2016).",
    "These affective states aren't a mere by-product though, but instead are a crucial feature of action selection.",
    "Unexpected increases or decreases alter the precision weighting on action policies (Van de Cruys 2017; Kiverstein et al. 2017)."
  ]
}